25 ab auditoriis et theatris: Dramatic performances were no longer given in Rome in the days of Vespasian, Maternus' plays, like those of Seneca, being book dramas Which the author recited before an audience, previous to their publication. The fictitious encounters of the drama enacted in recitation-halls are contrasted with the real contests of the orator in the forum. Cf. Pliny, Ep. II 3, 5 f. Nos enim qui in foro verisque litibus ferimur, multum malitiae . . . addiscimus. Schola et auditorium et ficta causa res inermis, innoxia est.
